<p>You can view and copy the source of this page:
</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">__FORCETOC__ 
The Goldeneye Reading Project is a [http://mech.ubc.ca/industry-and-alumni/45x-capstone-design/ 4th year Capstone project] at the [http://www.ubc.ca University of British Columbia]. Our objective is to provide ALS patients with the ability to retrieve and navigate readable content.  We've chosen to implement a solution using Tekla, a [http://www.archos.com/products/ta/archos_101it/index.html?country=us&amp;lang=en Archos 101 Internet Tablet] and Android e-reader and web browsing applications.

Although a low tech reading solution would be more widely accepted, we feel focusing on the Tekla user experience within a specific application genre will improve usability across the entire Android OS. People with ALS would benefit from other Android applications such as:

* AAC
* Environmental control
* E-mail
* Telephone functions


We have also identified that low cost e-reading devices have begun to push the industry into the digital realm. 

== Proposed Software Items ==

So far we have looked at 10 e-reading applications. For turning pages or scrolling through text, 7 of them were compatible with the Tekla d-pad events, but for navigation across the entire application only [https://market.android.com/details?id=com.amazon.kindle Amazon Kindle] and [https://market.android.com/details?id=com.aldiko.android Aldiko] provided a sufficient user experience because of their ability to use d-pad events.

To further improve the experience we are perusing development of the following features.

{|
! Feature
! Reason
! Possible Implementations
|-
| MENU button trigger
| Adding the menu button would enable access to the Kindle Store and allow changing text size and screen brightness across many applications.
| 
* Modification to &lt;code>kbd_ui.xml&lt;/code>
* Move nav bar to top when menu open?
* Are key codes realated to [http://source.android.com/porting/keymaps_keyboard_input.html input device key maps]?
|-
| Less intrusive nav bar
| The current keyboard layout for navigation obscures text when reading books.
| 
* Auto-hide navigation bar during inactivity. Could modify &lt;code>android:keyHeight&lt;/code>
* Use transparencies if possible.
|-
| 1/2 Switch Access
| In late stage ALS patients may be able to control a single switch; multiple switches may to too fatiguing or too difficult to coordinate.
Page turning (a binary command) consumes most of a user's time when reading. A single switch would map well to this function with little overhead.
| 
* Implement auto-scan with switch to select.
* Implement switch hold to scan and release to select.
|-
| HID Support
| Human Interface Device support as explained in the hardware section below. More information can be found on the [[HID/USB Support]] page.
| 
* Add 5 more bytes to the packet sent by the shield.
|-
|}


Jorge informed us in a meeting on February 7th 2010 that he has been instructed to add 1/2 switch access himself. He suggested that we proceed with the other two features by modifying the [[Tekla/Input Method | Tekla Input Method]].

== Proposed Hardware Items ==

[[File:Infogrip_giant_trackball.JPG|200px|thumb|right|An example of a high bandwidth input device, an Infogrip USB trackball.]]
The jump from touchscreen input to Tekla is not a natural progression and thus the user may be reluctant when faced with a new learning curve. We feel a more natural progression can be accomplished by introducing an intermediate step.

* Trackballs 
* Mice
* Joysticks

These devices allow the control mechanism to be separated from the viewing surface but still provide a high degree of control. In contrast, touchscreens are built into the display and cannot be moved to a comfortable position for control. Switches can be put in a comfortable position but are limited in bandwidth.


Two architectures for interfacing [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_interface_device Human Interface Devices] with Tekla have been considered.

{|
| 
[[File:high_bandwidth_bluetooth.jpg|300px]]
|
'''Add Support for Bluetooth HID'''

According to [http://code.google.com/p/android/issues/detail?id=1147 official issue threads] stock Android does not fully support [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bluetooth_profile#Human_Interface_Device_Profile_.28HID.29 HID devices over Bluetooth]. We suggest that the current capabilities of HID devices be tested and that a layer be added to the Tekla application to fully support them.

The Android project may support HID devices in the future.
|-
| 
[[File:high_bandwidth_usb.jpg|300px]]
|
'''Shield Upgrade'''

The current [[MEADL_Shield|Tekla shield]] has a [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D-subminiature DE-9] connector and a [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TRS_connector 3.5mm mono jack] which accept 4 and 1 switch inputs respectively. We suggest that USB ports capable of acting as hosts to HID devices be added in the next iteration.

Arduino can only host a USB connection with the help of a peripheral controller such as the [http://www.maxim-ic.com/datasheet/index.mvp/id/3639 MAX3421E] as demonstrated by the [http://www.circuitsathome.com/arduino_usb_host_shield_projects USB Host Shield].
|-
|}


We have decided to pursue the shield upgrade option which will require changes to [[Switch Event Provider]]. We will also test the extent of Android's support for Bluetooth HID devices.

More information can be found on the [[HID/USB Support]] page.

== Team Members ==

* Andrea Slade (Mechanical)
* Hengameh Hoseini (Biomedical)
* Kevin Lowe (Mechatronics)
* Rory Moglove (Integrated)


Our team is advised by [http://mech.ubc.ca/antony-hodgson/ Antony Hodgson] and [http://www.ece.ubc.ca/faculty/craig-hennessey-0 Craig Hennessey]. We can be contacted at goldeneye-ubc@googlegroups.com
